content.text:
Here is a concrete plan for each. I'll show exactly what to change and where.

---

## (a) Deductible — two separate fixes

### Fix 1: Formula order

The current formula in [adjudication.service.js:220-221](app/src/domain/services/adjudication.service.js#L220-L221):
```js
const coveredGross = item.billedAmount * (rule.coveredPercent / 100);
const afterDeductible = Math.max(0, coveredGross - rule.deductible);
```

Standard insurance applies the deductible to the billed amount first, then the coverage percent to the remainder:
```js
const afterDeductible = Math.max(0, item.billedAmount - rule.deductible);
const coveredGross = afterDeductible * (rule.coveredPercent / 100);
```
On a $1,000 claim at 80% with a $500 deductible: the current code gives $300, the standard formula gives $400. Update `approvalExplanation` too — it currently says "covered at 80% of the billed amount" which is false when the deductible is applied first.

**Update the test** in [adjudication.test.js:33](app/tests/domain/adjudication.test.js#L33) — the comment says `80% of 1000 = 800, minus $500 deductible = $300` and asserts $300. After the fix, it should assert $400 (`max(0, 1000-500) * 0.8`).

### Fix 2: Annual deductible accumulator

This is the bigger change. You need a `DeductibleLedger` — the same append-only pattern as `LimitLedger`, keyed on `(policyId, memberId, benefitCategory, periodStart)`.

**New file:** `app/src/domain/models/DeductibleLedger.js`
```js
// Same structure as LimitLedger.
// Entries: APPLY (deductible applied) | RELEASE (reversal during reprocess)
// computeApplied() = sum of APPLY - sum of RELEASE
// Remaining deductible = rule.deductible - computeApplied()
```

**New service:** `app/src/domain/services/deductible.service.js`
```js
// getApplied(policyId, memberId, benefitCategory, date) → amount applied so far this year
// apply(policyId, memberId, benefitCategory, date, claimId, claimItemId, amount, session) → amount actually consumed
// releaseAllForClaim(policyId, memberId, date, claimId, items, session)
```

**Updated adjudication math** (same file, around line 220):
```js
const deductibleRemaining = Math.max(
  0,
  rule.deductible - await deductibleService.getApplied(
    claim.policyId, claim.memberId, item.benefitCategory, claim.dateOfService, session
  )
);
const deductibleThisClaim = await deductibleService.apply(
  claim.policyId, claim.memberId, item.benefitCategory, claim.dateOfService,
  claim._id, item._id, Math.min(item.billedAmount, deductibleRemaining), session
);
const afterDeductible = Math.max(0, item.billedAmount - deductibleThisClaim);
const coveredGross = afterDeductible * (rule.coveredPercent / 100);
```

**`reprocessClaim` in claim.service.js** also needs to call `deductibleService.releaseAllForClaim(...)` in its transaction, just like it calls `limitService.releaseAllForClaim(...)`.

The `deductibleApplied` field on `ClaimDecision` already exists — now populate it correctly with `deductibleThisClaim`.

---

## (b) Three unfinished features

### b1: `isRetroactive` — the simplest correct interpretation

The flag should mean: "this version also governs claims whose date of service predates `effectiveFrom`, back to the previous version's `effectiveFrom`." The current query in [adjudication.service.js:22-32](app/src/domain/services/adjudication.service.js#L22-L32) ignores this entirely.

Update `findPolicyVersion` to fall back to a retroactive version:
```js
async function findPolicyVersion(policyId, dateOfService, session) {
  // Primary: exact date-range match
  const exact = await PolicyVersion.findOne(
    { policyId, effectiveFrom: { $lte: dateOfService },
      $or: [{ effectiveTo: null }, { effectiveTo: { $gte: dateOfService } }] },
    null, { session }
  ).sort({ effectiveFrom: -1 });

  if (exact) return exact;

  // Fallback: retroactive version — covers dates before its own effectiveFrom
  return PolicyVersion.findOne(
    { policyId, isRetroactive: true },
    null, { session }
  ).sort({ effectiveFrom: -1 });
}
```

Then add a test: create a claim for Jan 15, create a retroactive PolicyVersion effective Feb 1, confirm adjudication uses the Feb 1 version.

### b2: `NEEDS_REVIEW` — define the trigger and wire it up

Right now nothing sets it. Pick a concrete trigger — the simplest defensible one: **add `requiresManualReview: Boolean` to `coverageRuleSchema`** in [PolicyVersion.js](app/src/domain/models/PolicyVersion.js). When true, the item goes to `NEEDS_REVIEW` instead of being approved or denied.

In [adjudication.service.js](app/src/domain/services/adjudication.service.js), after the pre-auth check, add:
```js
if (rule.requiresManualReview) {
  // create a NEEDS_REVIEW decision (no amount consumed, no denial code)
  item.status = 'NEEDS_REVIEW';
  // don't increment approvedCount or deniedCount — it's in limbo
  continue;
}
```

Update claim status rollup (around line 270) to handle the third count:
```js
const needsReviewCount = claim.items.filter(i => i.status === 'NEEDS_REVIEW').length;
if (needsReviewCount > 0) {
  claim.status = 'UNDER_REVIEW'; // stays under review until manual adjudication resolves it
} else if (approvedCount === claim.items.length) {
  claim.status = 'APPROVED';
} else if (approvedCount > 0) {
  claim.status = 'PARTIALLY_APPROVED';
} else {
  claim.status = 'DENIED';
}
```

Add a new route for manual adjudication:
```
POST /claims/:id/items/:itemId/adjudicate
body: { decision: 'APPROVED' | 'DENIED', approvedAmount?, denialCode?, denialReason? }
roles: ADJUSTER, ADMIN
```
This endpoint updates the item status, creates a ClaimDecision, and re-evaluates the overall claim status.

### b3: Dispute resolution — close the loop

The Dispute model is complete. It just has no API surface. Add a route in [claims.js](app/src/api/routes/claims.js) and a `resolveDispute` method in [claim.service.js](app/src/domain/services/claim.service.js).

**New route:**
```
POST /claims/:id/dispute/resolve
roles: ADJUSTER, ADMIN
body: { decision: 'UPHELD' | 'REVERSED' | 'WITHDRAWN', resolution: string }
```

**New service method:**
```js
async function resolveDispute(claimId, decision, resolution, actorId) {
  const claim = await Claim.findById(claimId).populate('activeDisputeId');
  if (!claim?.activeDisputeId) throw ...; // 422 no active dispute

  const dispute = claim.activeDisputeId;
  dispute.status = decision;       // UPHELD | REVERSED | WITHDRAWN
  dispute.resolution = resolution;
  dispute.resolvedAt = new Date();
  dispute.resolvedBy = actorId;
  await dispute.save();            // triggers the pre-save guard that enforces resolvedBy

  claim.activeDisputeId = null;    // clear the pointer — dispute is closed
  if (decision === 'REVERSED') {
    claim.status = 'UNDER_REVIEW'; // will be reprocessed next
  } else {
    claim.status = claim.status;   // stays at current adjudicated status
  }
  await claim.save();

  return { dispute, claim };
}
```

If `decision === 'REVERSED'`, the caller should follow up with `POST /claims/:id/reprocess`. You can make that automatic in the route or document it explicitly — explicit is better.

---

## (c) Event bus — make a decision and commit to it

Right now it's 70+ lines of code across two files that do nothing. Pick one path:

**Option A — Remove it (recommended for the assignment).** Delete `eventBus.js`, `events.js`, and all `eventBus.emit(...)` calls. The audit trail already exists in `AuditLog` and the `ClaimDecision` supersession chain. Dead scaffolding in a take-home is a signal that you didn't review AI output.

**Option B — Wire it up.** If you want to keep the architecture, add a single structured-log subscriber in [app.js](app/src/app.js) at startup:
```js
const eventBus = require('./domain/events/eventBus');
const EVENTS = require('./domain/events/events');

const LOG_EVENTS = [EVENTS.CLAIM_ADJUDICATED, EVENTS.DISPUTE_FILED, EVENTS.BENEFIT_LIMIT_EXHAUSTED];
for (const event of LOG_EVENTS) {
  eventBus.on(event, (payload) => {
    process.stdout.write(JSON.stringify({ event, ...payload }) + '\n');
  });
}
```

Now there is at least one real subscriber. You can make the argument that the event bus is the extension point for future webhooks, notifications, or async reprocessing — but only if something actually listens to it today.

Don't keep both: zero subscribers with the emit calls is worse than either option.

---

## Auth bypass

Replace the ENV-conditional bypass with **test JWTs signed with a known test secret**. In your test setup file:

```js
// tests/helpers.js — add
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');
process.env.JWT_SECRET = 'test-secret-do-not-use-in-production';

function makeToken(id, role) {
  return jwt.sign({ sub: id, role }, process.env.JWT_SECRET, { expiresIn: '1h' });
}
```

Then in tests, pass `Authorization: Bearer ${makeToken(member._id, 'MEMBER')}` instead of the `X-Test-Actor` header. Delete the `NODE_ENV=test` branch in [auth.js:6-18](app/src/api/middleware/auth.js#L6-L18) entirely. The auth middleware now runs the same code path in tests as in production. Bugs in JWT handling get caught by tests, not bypassed by them.

---

## Referential validation

Add this check at the top of `submitClaim` in [claim.service.js](app/src/domain/services/claim.service.js) before saving:

```js
async function submitClaim(claimData) {
  const policy = await Policy.findById(claimData.policyId);
  if (!policy) throw Object.assign(new Error('Policy not found'), { statusCode: 404 });
  if (policy.memberId.toString() !== claimData.memberId.toString()) {
    throw Object.assign(new Error('Policy does not belong to this member'), { statusCode: 403 });
  }
  if (policy.status !== 'ACTIVE') {
    throw Object.assign(new Error(`Policy is ${policy.status}`), { statusCode: 422 });
  }
  // ... existing save logic
}
```

Also add the policy status check to [adjudication.service.js](app/src/domain/services/adjudication.service.js) — load the Policy after loading the Claim, check `policy.status`, and deny all items with `POLICY_INACTIVE` if it's not ACTIVE. This catches the case where a policy is terminated after claim submission but before adjudication.

---

### Order of priority

If you're time-boxing, tackle these in this order:

1. **Referential validation** — one-liner that closes a real authorization hole
2. **Deductible formula** — one-line fix, update one test assertion
3. **Dispute resolution API** — small surface, closes a half-built feature with visible impact
4. **Event bus** — make a decision and commit; removing it is 20 minutes
5. **Annual deductible accumulator** — correct but scope-heavy; document clearly if you skip it
6. `isRetroactive` and `NEEDS_REVIEW` — implement or delete the fields; don't leave them as inert schema

